description:
You are a machine-learning engineer doing a quick sanity-check on a small JSON data file before feeding it into a model-training pipeline.  
A colleague has already written an informal JSON-Schema (see feature_schema.json) that documents the expected structure, but what you really need right now is just a fast, one-liner jq command to:

1. read /home/user/data/training_samples.json (it is a single top-level array of objects);  
2. keep only those objects that simultaneously satisfy all of the following field-level rules:  
   • “id” exists and is a string;  
   • “features” exists, is an array whose length is exactly 3, and every item is a number;  
   • “label” exists and its value is either the literal string "positive" or "negative".  
   Objects can contain **extra** keys without being rejected.  
3. write the filtered, **minified** JSON array (no newlines or spaces except those produced by jq’s “-c” flag) to /home/user/output/valid_samples.json;  
4. create /home/user/output/validation.log that contains exactly three lines, each terminated by a single UNIX newline (LF), in this precise order and spelling:  

Total:&lt;N&gt;  
Valid:&lt;M&gt;  
Invalid:&lt;K&gt;  

…where &lt;N&gt; is the total number of top-level objects in training_samples.json, &lt;M&gt; is how many remained after the filter, and &lt;K&gt; =&nbsp;&lt;N&gt;-&lt;M&gt;.  Make sure there are no extra spaces, tabs, or blank lines.

You do NOT need to perform full standards-compliant JSON-Schema validation or install any external tools; a single jq pipeline is enough.  Aim for a succinct one-liner (though you may run it piecemeal while developing).

When you are done, both /home/user/output/valid_samples.json and /home/user/output/validation.log must exist and contain exactly the required contents so the automated grader can diff them verbatim.
